# DO-330 meta / TOR-FM-04 discrimination oracle — GENUINE nondeterminism defect.
#
# In COMPILED (default) mode the deployed pure-Simple binary prints a list value
# as its heap-object identity `<array@0xADDR>` instead of its elements. That
# address is chosen by the allocator on top of an ASLR-randomised mapping, so it
# VARIES run-to-run:
#     <array@0x4b5fc03e9a0>   <array@0x5214603e9a0>   <array@0x3783003e9a0>   ...
# In INTERPRET mode the same program prints the correct, deterministic `[1, 2, 3]`
# — so this is also a mode divergence, but TOR-FM-04 only concerns run-to-run
# reproducibility within one mode. Observed varying across runs on 2026-07-06
# (host randomize_va_space=2) before being pinned here as the discrimination
# oracle for scripts/check/cert/tool-qual-meta.shs --self-test.
#
# This file is deliberately EXCLUDED from the determinism gate (the gate walks
# meta/deterministic/ only). It is retained as reproducible evidence of a real
# compiled-mode identity-leak defect, exactly as known_defects/ retains triaged
# silent-accepts. Do NOT "fix" it into a deterministic program — its whole value
# is that it varies.
fn main():
    val xs = [1, 2, 3]
    print(xs)
